rom Judea’, borne by a Jewish heroine whose story is recorded in the Book of Judith in the Apocrypha. Judith is portrayed as a beautiful widow who delivers her people from the invading Assyrians by gaining the confidence of their commander, Holofernes, and cutting off his head while he is asleep; without their commander, the Assyrians are duly routed. This has been a perennially popular Jewish name. In the English-speaking world it was taken up in the 16th century, having been in occasional use among Gentiles before this: for example, it was borne by a niece of William the Conqueror. It enjoyed great popularity between the 1940s and the 1960s. Today's notable bearers include the American novelist  Judith Krantz  (  b. 1928 ) and the Scottish composer  Judith Weir  (  b. 1954 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Judith of Normandy was born about 0985, in Brittany, France. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Geoffroi de Rennes. She died in 1034, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 0985–1034":"umbes 0985–1034","0980–1046":"0980–1046","1015–1046":"1015–1046","0996–1040":"0996–1040","0999–1079":"0999–1079","1053–1094":"1053–1094","0985–1034":"0985–1034","1053":"1053","1040":"1040","1094":"1094","0996":"0996","0985":"0985","about 0985":"umbes 0985","1015":"1015","1079":"1079","1046":"1046","1034":"1034","0980":"0980","999":"0999","0999":"0999","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Bretagne, Normandy, France":"Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","of Brittany & Ponthieve":"Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Vannes, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Vannes, Morbihan, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 0985–1034":"noin 0985–1034","0980–1046":"0980–1046","1015–1046":"1015–1046","0996–1040":"0996–1040","0999–1079":"0999–1079","1053–1094":"1053–1094","0985–1034":"0985–1034","1053":"1053","1040":"1040","1094":"1094","0996":"0996","0985":"0985","about 0985":"noin 0985","1015":"1015","1079":"1079","1046":"1046","1034":"1034","0980":"0980","999":"0999","0999